)] from other particles in the fluid and the membrane. The main factors affecting the separation of particles through pores on the membrane surface include convection force (
F c
), gravity (
F g
), back-diffusion force (
F b
), and friction force (
F f
). The size of a typical CMP slurry particle is in the range of several tens to hundreds of nano-scales, and convection force dominates particle separation in the corresponding area. The tangential drag force (
F t
), which flows the fluid containing particles in the retentate direction, is composed of the sum of various components. The magnitude of the tangential drag force is greatly affected by the flow rate, and the shear-stress force composing it controls the thickness of the filter cake layer. Hence, it is important to understand convection force (
F c
) and tangential drag force (
F t
) to adjust the separation rate in the TFF system.
